{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655851"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:06:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:06:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18685"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18685"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11417"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62345"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10294"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26455"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlutamate is released from presynaptic terminals throughout the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism by which glutamate produces excitation of postsynaptic neurons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates sodium-potassium ATPase","Activates adenylate cyclase","Closes potassium channels","Opens sodium and calcium channels via ionotropic receptors","Inhibits chloride entry"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary excitatory mechanism of glutamate involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eopening sodium and calcium channels via ionotropic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. When glutamate binds to AMPA, NMDA or kainate receptors, these ion channels open directly, allowing sodium and calcium ions to enter the postsynaptic neuron. This causes membrane depolarisation and neuronal excitation.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivates adenylate cyclase\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a second messenger pathway used by metabotropic receptors, not the primary excitatory mechanism of glutamate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECloses potassium channels\u003C/strong\u003E - While this would cause excitation, it is not how glutamate primarily works\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits chloride entry\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more characteristic of GABA receptor antagonists\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates sodium-potassium ATPase\u003C/strong\u003E - This would hyperpolarise the membrane and cause inhibition, not excitation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rapid opening of ion channels through ionotropic receptors allows for fast synaptic transmission, which is essential for normal central nervous system function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glutamate is the primary excitatory neurotransmitter in the central nervous system.","Glutamate acts via ionotropic receptors (AMPA, NMDA, kainate) and metabotropic receptors.","Ionotropic glutamate receptors directly open ion channels to allow sodium and calcium entry into the postsynaptic neuron."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"